WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.820
You've learned the sales process.

2
00:00:02.260 --> 00:00:03.420
You've practiced calls.

3
00:00:03.820 --> 00:00:08.240
You know the tools. Now we need to talk
about how we know if any of that is actually

4
00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:12.520
working. Because in this business, feelings
don't close deals.

5
00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:13.940
Numbers do.

6
00:00:15.320 --> 00:00:17.400
You can feel like you had a productive day.

7
00:00:17.680 --> 00:00:19.280
Feel like you're making progress.

8
00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:21.240
Feel like things are going well.

9
00:00:21.620 --> 00:00:23.040
And still be falling behind.

10
00:00:23.700 --> 00:00:24.960
That happens all the time.

11
00:00:24.960 --> 00:00:29.840
The people who improve fastest are the ones
who actually look at their numbers, figure

12
00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:32.140
out where the gaps are, and fix them.

13
00:00:32.540 --> 00:00:34.660
Everyone else just guesses and hopes.

14
00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:39.220
KPI stands for Key Performance Indicator.

15
00:00:39.700 --> 00:00:44.700
These are the numbers that tell you and your
manager whether you're on track or not.

16
00:00:45.080 --> 00:00:47.620
Think of them like the dashboard in your
car.

17
00:00:47.620 --> 00:00:52.600
You don't need to be a mechanic to know that
if your fuel gauge is on empty, you've got

18
00:00:52.600 --> 00:00:55.180
a problem. KPIs work the same way.

19
00:00:55.500 --> 00:00:59.200
One glance and you know where you're strong
and where something needs fixing.

20
00:01:00.500 --> 00:01:04.300
The biggest mistake people make when they
start is flying blind.

21
00:01:04.660 --> 00:01:09.980
Making calls all day, staying busy, feeling
productive, but never actually checking

22
00:01:09.980 --> 00:01:11.700
whether any of it is converting.

23
00:01:11.700 --> 00:01:16.220
Being busy and being productive are two
completely different things.

24
00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:19.420
And KPIs are what separates them.

25
00:01:20.660 --> 00:01:24.220
We track six metrics and we track them from
left to right.

26
00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:29.540
That means we follow the lead from the moment
it enters the pipeline all the way to a

27
00:01:29.540 --> 00:01:30.500
signed contract.

28
00:01:30.880 --> 00:01:32.720
Each metric feeds into the next.

29
00:01:33.160 --> 00:01:37.000
And when something breaks, you can trace it
back to exactly where it broke.

30
00:01:37.940 --> 00:01:40.460
The first metric is dial count.

31
00:01:41.100 --> 00:01:44.500
This is the total number of outbound calls
you make in a day.

32
00:01:44.780 --> 00:01:47.840
It's one of the clearest measures of
outbound effort.

33
00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:53.340
You can't control whether someone picks up,
you can't control whether they want to sell,

34
00:01:53.340 --> 00:01:59.080
but you can control whether you keep working
the list with real effort and consistency.

35
00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:02.160
Now here's something worth explaining.

36
00:02:02.900 --> 00:02:08.280
We do not hold people to a strict dial count
as the goal by itself.

37
00:02:08.620 --> 00:02:13.120
If someone is chasing a number late in the
day, they can start speed dialing through

38
00:02:13.120 --> 00:02:15.400
their list just to make the count look
right.

39
00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:21.960
No real conversations, no quality, just
tapping the phone as fast as possible.

40
00:02:22.140 --> 00:02:23.940
That's completely useless.

41
00:02:23.940 --> 00:02:30.260
So we track dial count as a leading
indicator of effort, but it is not the

42
00:02:30.260 --> 00:02:35.680
goal. It tells us whether someone is putting
in the work, but the work itself has to be

43
00:02:35.680 --> 00:02:36.000
real.

44
00:02:37.320 --> 00:02:39.460
The second metric is connection rate.

45
00:02:39.780 --> 00:02:43.340
Out of all those dials, how many people
actually picked up?

46
00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:47.840
This one tells you about list quality and
whether your phone number is getting flagged

47
00:02:47.840 --> 00:02:48.460
as spam.

48
00:02:48.460 --> 00:02:53.140
If your connection rate drops below the normal
range for your role in market, something

49
00:02:53.140 --> 00:02:58.260
is wrong. Your number might be getting marked
as spam, the list might be stale, or you

50
00:02:58.260 --> 00:02:59.860
might be calling at bad times.

51
00:02:59.980 --> 00:03:04.060
If you see that happening, flag it to your
manager right away.

52
00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:08.020
The third metric is quality conversations.

53
00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:12.500
Out of the people who picked up, how many of
them genuinely want to sell?

54
00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:14.640
This doesn't mean they'll accept our price.

55
00:03:14.840 --> 00:03:18.440
It means they have a property and they're
interested in hearing an offer.

56
00:03:19.020 --> 00:03:21.840
A quality conversation filters out wrong
numbers.

57
00:03:22.280 --> 00:03:27.120
People who say, take me off your list, and
people who have zero interest in selling.

58
00:03:27.540 --> 00:03:33.080
If that number is low, it usually means the
list is off, your opening isn't connecting,

59
00:03:33.080 --> 00:03:37.200
or you're calling into a market where the
leads aren't matched to what we do.

60
00:03:37.960 --> 00:03:40.660
The fourth metric is process calls.

61
00:03:41.340 --> 00:03:46.160
Out of those quality conversations, how many
went all the way through your qualification

62
00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:47.600
and discovery process?

63
00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:53.760
This means you ran the full fact find,
confirmed they qualify for our offer, gathered

64
00:03:53.760 --> 00:03:56.060
all the information needed to move forward.

65
00:03:56.060 --> 00:04:01.760
If your quality conversations are high, but
your process calls are low, you're probably

66
00:04:01.760 --> 00:04:07.560
disqualifying people too fast, not handling
objections well enough, or not going deep

67
00:04:07.560 --> 00:04:09.520
enough in your discovery conversations.

68
00:04:10.020 --> 00:04:14.240
That's a coaching moment, and it usually
shows up clearly in call recordings.

69
00:04:15.700 --> 00:04:17.660
The fifth metric is offers made.

70
00:04:18.200 --> 00:04:21.400
How many official offers went out from the
acquisition team?

71
00:04:21.400 --> 00:04:26.220
This is primarily tracked on their side, but
it reflects the quality of leads you're

72
00:04:26.220 --> 00:04:26.880
handing off.

73
00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:31.980
If the acquisition team is having lots of
conversations but making very few offers, the

74
00:04:31.980 --> 00:04:35.840
leads coming across might not be as
qualified as they looked on paper.

75
00:04:36.540 --> 00:04:37.800
That's worth looking into.

76
00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:42.020
The sixth metric is contracts signed.

77
00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:44.900
This is the one everyone cares about.

78
00:04:45.740 --> 00:04:49.160
How many offers turned into signed
contracts?

79
00:04:49.660 --> 00:04:54.140
If that conversion is weaker than expected,
something in the negotiation or pricing

80
00:04:54.140 --> 00:04:55.960
process needs attention.

81
00:04:57.260 --> 00:05:01.680
The reason we track left to right is that
when something is off, you can pinpoint

82
00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:03.760
exactly where the breakdown is happening.

83
00:05:03.760 --> 00:05:06.600
Low dials? That's an effort problem.

84
00:05:07.140 --> 00:05:08.780
Good dials but low connections?

85
00:05:09.200 --> 00:05:11.120
Check the phone number and list quality.

86
00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:14.280
Good connections but few quality
conversations?

87
00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:17.460
The audience is wrong or the opening needs
work.

88
00:05:18.040 --> 00:05:20.420
Good conversations but few process calls?

89
00:05:20.860 --> 00:05:24.820
Discovery is weak or you're disqualifying
too fast.

90
00:05:24.820 --> 00:05:27.360
Good process calls but few offers?

91
00:05:27.900 --> 00:05:29.440
The handoff might be incomplete.

92
00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:31.920
Good offers but few contracts?

93
00:05:32.440 --> 00:05:34.160
Something's off in the negotiation.

94
00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:37.380
Each step narrows the funnel.

95
00:05:37.900 --> 00:05:42.580
Your job is to keep the funnel as healthy as
possible at the stages you control, which

96
00:05:42.580 --> 00:05:44.960
is everything from dials through handoff.

97
00:05:45.980 --> 00:05:50.360
The question is always, where's the gap and
what do we do about it?

98
00:05:50.700 --> 00:05:55.820
If your dials are low, is it an effort issue
or are you spending too long on individual

99
00:05:55.820 --> 00:05:57.420
calls and running out of time?

100
00:05:57.740 --> 00:06:01.860
If your conversations aren't converting, do
we need to pull up your recordings and

101
00:06:01.860 --> 00:06:02.640
listen together?

102
00:06:02.860 --> 00:06:07.740
If your process calls are dropping, are you
disqualifying people too aggressively based

103
00:06:07.740 --> 00:06:09.080
on the first thing they say?

104
00:06:09.260 --> 00:06:11.040
That's the whole point of tracking.

105
00:06:11.960 --> 00:06:16.980
Not to micromanage, not to punish, to find
the gaps and close them.

106
00:06:17.300 --> 00:06:21.800
The people who embrace their numbers instead
of avoiding them are the ones who improve

107
00:06:21.800 --> 00:06:22.640
the fastest.

108
00:06:23.160 --> 00:06:25.840
So know your numbers. Look at them every
day.

109
00:06:26.180 --> 00:06:29.860
And when something looks off, don't ignore
it.

110
00:06:31.080 --> 00:06:32.480
You've got the numbers down.

111
00:06:33.120 --> 00:06:37.780
Next up, we'll talk about exactly how your
work translates into what you take home.

112
00:06:37.780 --> 00:06:40.820
The offer letter you'll sign is where that
gets spelled out.
